<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Charles Petrie, Coordinator of the Norwegian sponsored Myanmar Peace Support Initiative</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Written evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Charles Petrie</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Coordinator of the Norwegian sponsored </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Myanmar</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Peace Support Initiative</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Context</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The peace process</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> which emerged in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Myanmar/Burma</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> in late 2011</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> represents the best opportunity in many decades to address issues </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> have structured armed conflict in the country since independence.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> The agreement of ceasefires is a historically important achievement of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">peace making</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">But t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he ceasefires are not ends in themselves. They create the space and opportunity for the resolution of historical differences through political dialogue.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The peace process emerged as a government-led initiative, under the leadership of President U Thein Sein, and his chief peace envoy, Minister U Aung Min. Although questions remain regarding the government’s ability to deliver on agreements negotiated with Ethnic Armed Groups, most stakeholders acknowledge the vision, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">leadership and commitment of the President and his team.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">[</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The changes in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Myanmar/Burma</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> are real and irreversible. The change</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Myanmar/Burma</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> are</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> as much an outcome of the structural transformation of power (</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the 2010 elections resulting in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the civilianization of the regime) as </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">they are</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> a result of a new political will</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> developed by reformists within the government</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">. The civilianization of the regime introduced a new generation of leaders</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, under the direction of the President,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> who underst</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">oo</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">d the precarity of the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> socio-economic situation they we</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">re inheriting.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> This sentiment among the reformists was further accentuated by the violence of the Saffron Revolution and destructive impact of Cyclone Nargis. It is very difficult to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">envisage</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> how it w</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ould</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> be possible for any hard-line regime</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> to reapply the oppression of the past on a population that has </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">f</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">el</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> an easing of the constraints impo</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">sed upon it</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">. T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">o which should be added the loss of religious legitimacy of the military regime after the violent crackdown on monks during</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> the Saffron Revolution in 2007</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">]</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Over the past year, Ethnic Armed Groups have been increasingly pro-active and creative in their relationships with the government, during negotiations to achieve a Nationwide Ceasefire Agreement. Although tensions and difficulties still exist, Ethnic Armed Groups have demonstrated commitment to the peace process, and eagerness to begin necessary political dialogue.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The leaders of the Ethnic Armed Groups acknowledge and expect that the political dialogue process will take time</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he time necessary to reach an acceptable outcome. As such the 2015 elections are seen as creating a temporary interruption in a process that will go on until 2020. And as such they wish to ensure that arrangements be agreed prior to the dialogue to allow the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> to function during the interim period defined by the political dialogue process. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The ceasefires and emerging peace process are helping to transform the lives of civilians affected by decades of armed conflict.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">isplaced people are beginning to return to previous settlements and attempting to rebuild their lives. In many communities, livelihoods have improved as a result of villagers’ better access to their f</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ields</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and a reduction in predatory taxation. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Through a series of “listening projects”, it has become evident that v</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">illagers greatly appreciate these changes, although they worry whether the ceasefire</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">s can be maintained</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">peace process </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">sustained</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The peace process in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Myanmar/Burma</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> is unique in many ways, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">not least because of the limited role of the international community. Negotiations are </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">undertaken </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">directly </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">between the government and ethnic armed groups, with no significant external mediation and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">only limited international facilitation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">International support to the peace process in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Myanmar/Burma</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> have to be understood in a global context where </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">aid donors tend to frame the concerns of vulnerable communities as technical problems to be fixed by professional aid regimes, rather than sites of contestation requiring political solutions.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he problem in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Myanmar/Burma</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> is not primarily a failing or weak state that needs to be strengthened or fixed, but rather an urgent need to re-imagine and negotiate state-society relations – and in particular mend relationships between the Burman majority and ethnic nationality communities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Aid agencies working in conflict-affected areas need to better understand local political cultures and perceptions, and the dynamics of peace and conflict. International donors and diplomats need to better demonstrate their understanding of the complexities in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Myanmar/Burma</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, and play a more strategic role in supporting the peace process.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The current state of economic and political development of the country could be dramatically altered with the rise of religious violence. In an ironic way, the opening up of political and public space has allowed greater freedom of expression to promoters of hate and exclusion.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The challenge </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the UK Government </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">is less to ensure that the situation does not revert to that of the past</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> or wait for a more favourable outcome in 2015</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, but more how to accompany </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">dramatic transformative </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">process </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">underway in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Myanmar/Burma</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">towards an acceptable outcome. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Given the precarity of any dramatic transformation, i</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">t is important to engage now.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The causes for concern </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">resulting from any delay in support </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">are multiple and include</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">, (i) t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he lack, within the current authority, of the necessary experience and education to develop with confidence many of the much needed socio-economic policies;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> (ii) </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">he limited understanding of the new authorities (and even the leaders of the ethnic armed groups) of the nature of the underlying tensions that fuel violence in many parts of the country</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">; (iii)</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the difficulty in countering the unscrupulous exploitation of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Myanmar/</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Burma’s wealth by economic actors from within and outside the country; and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">(iv) d</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ealing with the frustrations of a population who do not see quickly enough the benefits of change (and the non-civilianized military no longer clear about future prospects).</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">The time </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">is now </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">for DFID to increase funding </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">in support of efforts </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">back</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the reformers</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">Specifically, (</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">) b</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">uilding</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> the capacity of the Government to manage the new socio-economic and political realities (through direct programme interventions, supporting initiatives to provide immediate and direct techn</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">ical support to the government), (ii) directly supporting the peace process (through the establishment of a multi-donor peace fund and direct contributions to it),</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">(iii) s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">upporting </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the ability of the Armed Ethnic Groups to survive the interim period necessary for political dialogue (to include supporting </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the financial survival of the armed groups through the predictable taxation of the areas they control, the continued provision of basic services </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">by the administrative arms of the Armed Ethnic Groups </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">to the populations under their control, and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">promoting </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">the clear delineation and respect of areas of authority</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>